{"text": "(55.3)\n\nIt is argued that the weak interaction with an environment that has a huge density of state \u03c1env leads after relaxation\n\nto a canonical state which is determined by the parameter \u03b2 = d log(\u03c1env(E))/dE that characterizes the environment.\n\nThe argument is based on the assumption that the universe (system+environment) is a closed system with some total\n\nenergy Etotal. After ergodization the system get into a stationary-like state. The probability pr to find the system in\n\nstate Er is proportional to \u03c1env(Etotal\u2212Er) \u2248\u03c1env(Etotal)e\u2212\u03b2Er. Accordingly\n\npr = 1\n\nZ e\u2212\u03b2Er\n\n(55.4)\n\nwhere the so-called partition function provides the normalization\n\nZ (\u03b2; X) =\n\nX\n\nr\n\ne\u2212\u03b2Er\n\n(55.5)\n\nOne observes that the energy can be obtained from\n\nE\n\n=\n\n\u2212\u2202ln Z\n\n\u2202\u03b2\n\n(55.6)\n\nwhile the generalized force is\n\ny\n\n=\n\n1\n\n\u03b2\n\n\u2202ln Z\n\n\u2202X\n\n(55.7)\n\nIf we slightly change X and \u03b2 and assume that the state of the system remains canonical then\n\ndE\n\n=\n\nX\n\nr\n\ndprEr +\n\nX\n\nprdEr\n\n\u2261\n\nTdS \u2212ydX\n\n(55.8)\n\nwhere the absolute temperature is defined as the integration factor of the first term\n\nT\n\n=\n\nintegration factor\n\n=\n\n1\n\n\u03b2\n\n(55.9)\n\n293\n\nand the implied definition of the thermodynamic entropy is\n\nS\n\n=\n\n\u2212\n\nX\n\npr ln pr\n\n(55.10)\n\nNote that the thermodynamic entropy is an extensive quantity in the thermodynamic limit.\n\nAt this state it is\n\nconvenient to define the Helmholtz generating function\n\nF(T, X)\n\n\u2261\n\n\u22121\n\n\u03b2 ln Z(\u03b2; X)\n\n(55.11)\n\nwhich allows to write the state equation in an elegant way:\n\nS = \u2212\u2202F\n\n\u2202T\n\n(55.12)\n\ny = \u2212\u2202F\n\n\u2202X\n\n(55.13)\n\nand\n\nE = F + TS\n\n(55.14)\n\n====== [55.2] Work\n\nIn the definition of work the system and the environment are regarded as one driven closed unit. On the basis of the\n\n\u201crate of change formula\u201d we have the following exact expression:\n\nW\n\n=\n\n\u2212\n\nZ\n\n\u27e8F \u27e9t dX\n\n(55.15)\n\nwhere F = \u2212dH/dX. Note that \u27e8F\u27e9t is calculated for the time dependent (evolving) state of the system.", "embedding": [-0.014136209, 0.03852182, 0.056711312, 0.007885594, -0.028924193, -0.013607198, -0.03471565, 0.00061136903, -0.07810922, 0.080845535, 0.05155678, -0.0066503547, 0.0052021956, -0.017026413, -0.011505457, -0.011580816, -0.028216684, -0.006972169, -0.09375399, 0.028903827, 0.009369834, 0.012254468, -0.05954645, -0.057960477, -0.029844781, 0.031647533, 0.045141827, 0.01577206, 0.06154815, 0.047815975, 0.0301813, -0.04592521, -0.009516165, -0.0396235, -0.006018028, -0.0023865814, 0.014445562, -0.026099298, 0.03677358, -0.044101972, 0.0566285, 0.014186735, 0.026611459, -0.013437791, -0.041884527, 0.023240339, -0.0120788105, 0.006633924, -0.021943374, -0.06990013, 0.019231549, 0.020239007, 0.034606736, -0.072337426, 0.034606244, 0.015024408, -0.009766094, 0.043381028, -0.014264132, 0.052753303, 0.06253605, 0.021491759, 0.0634733, -0.04242206, -0.008500408, 0.06962192, 9.468331e-05, 0.04864897, -0.01357197, -0.008744444, -0.009835335, -0.0068340283, -0.036184885, -0.0070540155, -0.038582675, 0.054711994, 0.03859569, -0.015484324, -0.016189229, -0.01438304, 0.022469413, 0.027038362, 0.0076598977, 0.036189273, -0.008371519, -0.023302142, 0.006039216, -0.016140345, -0.01726128, -0.01620312, 0.023655666, 0.060252424, -0.009209392, 0.002229867, -0.014398439, 0.036765948, -0.032969538, 0.049518183, 0.030377146, 0.009135924, 0.007153935, 0.070324555, -0.03452555, 0.035574052, -0.010807433, 0.044110883, 0.00948792, 0.031997707, -0.016499754, -0.059613187, 0.015085, 0.030053811, 0.0062891277, 0.020300899, 0.0060728895, 0.027059948, 0.035434127, 0.0038500046, -0.04971564, -0.024810513, -0.009375587, -0.0063265893, -0.008425885, 0.01910558, -0.0031200582, -0.028549844, -0.014178129, 0.0048036673, 0.00194626